The Kenya Film Classification Board is cracking down on public service vehicles screening pornographic content. According to the board CEO, Ezekiel Mutua, the crackdown follows complaints from the public. ALSO READ:

KFCB targets non-compliant filmmakers in a crackdown According to the board, some of the PSVs have become a nuisance screening, obscene content and playing loud music, violating the rights of passengers. Operators who wish to continue screening videos will have to get a licence at a cost of Sh2,000.